106-108 East 54th Street, adjoining and east of the S.E. corner of Park Ave.
About 1912.

401 Park Avenue, at N. E. corner of 54th Street, showing a newly completed prize-winning apartment house, 12 stories tall. On the further side of the garage, which will stay, another apartment house will be erected in 1916. Note the temporary wooden fence. The railroad tracks have been electrified and covered over, but the center parks have not yet been constructed. 1913.

Wurts Bros., Photographers..
Gift of E.M. Jenks.

54th Street, Park to Lexington Avenue.
(Before reconstruction).
August 2, 1920.

54th Street, Park, to Lexington Avenue.
August 2, 1920.

Park Avenue, south from 54th Street with New York Central Building in center background, newly completed, the newest building in the picture. By far the oldest building in sight is No. 378 to the extreme right, on the N.W. corner of 53rd Street. The Racquet and Tennis Club is the building just south of it. On the east side of the Avenue, the Hotel Ambassador between 52nd and 51st Street hides St. Bartholomew's Church. The next visible building on that side is the Railroad Y.M.C.A., where the new Waldorf Astoria will open in October 1931. April 24, 1928.

Park Avenue, west side, between 54th and 53rd Streets, the oldest complete block in this part of the Avenue, dating back to the 1890's or earlier.
These houses may be identified on 1905 photographs which show open railroad yards where the street now runs.
April 1928.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.
